## §10. How Solid Is the #1 Ranking?

- Bootstrap (20,000 re-draws): #1 in << f("boot.p_rank1") >>% of re-runs; top 3 in << f("boot.p_top3") >>%; top 5 in << f("boot.p_top5") >>%. 90% interval on adj margin: [<< f("boot.ci.lo") >>, << f("boot.ci.hi") >>].
- Empirical-Bayes shrinkage: << f("ats.n_total") >> games pin down only << f("shrink.weight_data") >>% of estimate; shrunken margin << f("shrink.post_mean") >> pts/game (95% CI [<< f("shrink.ci.lo") >>, << f("shrink.ci.hi") >>]), still beats << f("shrink.pct_above") >>% of champions.
- Adding opponent-SRS uncertainty barely moves result: #1 chance stays ~<< f("se_boot.p_rank1") >>%. Game variance dominates.
- Hierarchical (partial-pooling) test — every champion treated as uncertain: Knicks posterior mean << f("hier.post_mean") >> pts/game (90% CI [<< f("hier.ci.lo") >>, << f("hier.ci.hi") >>]). P(true #1) = << f("hier.p_rank1", "{:.0f}") >>%. P(top 3) = << f("hier.p_top3") >>%. Median rank << f("hier.rank_median") >>.
- Streakiness (huge sweeps + tight Finals) makes the run weaker evidence than a steady one — hence the hard pull from << f("adj.margin", "{:+.1f}") >> to ~<< f("hier.post_mean", "{:+.1f}") >> in the hierarchical model.
- Honest bottom line: clearly elite, very likely top-handful all-time, but data cannot crown them the single best. Chance of being true #1 runs from ~<< f("boot.p_rank1", "{:.0f}") >>% (holding history fixed) to ~<< f("hier.p_rank1", "{:.0f}") >>% (fairest test).
- knicks_2026_historic_results.md refs: §13 ROBUSTNESS, §14 HIERARCHICAL

## §11. A Second Opinion: Other Rating Systems

- Bradley-Terry (wins-only, no margins): Knicks adj margin << f("bt.adj_margin") >>, rank #<< f("bt.rank") >> of << f("raw.n_champions") >>. Correlation with SRS-adjusted: << f("bt.corr_srs") >>. Blowouts are not an artifact — dominance is real.
- Capped-margin SRS (clip each game at ±<< f("capped.cap") >>, robust to blowouts): adj margin << f("capped.adj_margin") >>, rank #<< f("capped.rank") >> of << f("raw.n_champions") >>, corr with SRS << f("capped.corr_srs") >>. Schedule strength isn't a blowout artifact either.
- Elo (recency-weighted): opp rating << f("elo.opp_rating") >> (tougher than SRS's << f("opp.srs_weighted") >> — opponents played well down the stretch). Elo-adjusted margin << f("elo.adj_margin") >>, rank #<< f("elo.rank") >> of << f("raw.n_champions") >> (behind 2016-17 Warriors and 1990-91 Bulls).
- All four systems put Knicks in top three (#1 on three; #3 only on Elo). What shifts them off #1 is crediting opponents' recent form (Elo), not stripping out margins (BT) or capping blowouts.
- knicks_2026_historic_results.md refs: §15 ELO CROSS-CHECK, §16 WINS-ONLY (BRADLEY-TERRY) CROSS-CHECK, §21 CAPPED-MARGIN (ROBUST) SRS CROSS-CHECK

